    <article>
      <h2 class="diary-title title is-size-2" id="9-ego-is-the-enemy">
        <a href="#9-ego-is-the-enemy">Ego is the Enemy, Ryan Holiday</a>
      </h2>

      <section class="content">
        <blockquote>
          <p>Do not believe that he who seeks to comfort you lives untroubled among the simple and quiet words that sometimes do you good. His life has much difficulty and sadness and remains far behind yours. Were it otherwise he would never have been able to find those words.</p>

          <p>There is no one moment that changes a person. There are many.</p>

          <p>The first principle is that you must not fool yourself &mdash; and you are the easiest person to fool.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;If you start believing in your greatness, it is the death of your creativity.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>We can seek to rationalize the worst behaviour by pointing to outliers. But no one is truly successful because they are delusional, self-absorbed, or disconnected.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;Be natural and yourself and this glittering flattery will be as the passing breeze of the sea on a warm summer day.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>Detachment is a sort of natural ego antidote. It&rsquo;s easy to be emotionally invested and infatuated with your own work. Any and every narcissist can do that. What is rare is not raw talent, skill, or even confidence, but humility, dilligence and self-awareness.</p>

          <p>In his famous 1934 campaign for the governorship of California, the author and activist Upton Sinclair took an unusual step. Before the election, he published a short book titled I, Governor of California and How I Ended Poverty, in which he outlined, in the past tense, the brilliant policies he had enacted as governor... the office he had not yet won.</p>

          <p>It&rsquo;s a temptation that exists for everyone &mdash; for talk and hype to replace action.</p>

          <p>[...] she did what a lot of us do when we&rsquo;re scared or overwhelmend by a project: she did everything but focus on it.</p>

          <p>[...] many valuable endeavours we undertake are painfully difficult, whether it&rsquo;s coding a new startup or mastering a craft. But talking, talking is always easy.</p>

          <p>Talk depletes us. Talking and doing fight for the same resources. Research shows that while goal visualization is important, after a certain point our mind begins to confuse it with actual progress. The same goes for verbalization. Even talking aloud to ourselves while we work through difficult problems has been shown to significantly decrease insight and breakthroughs. After spending so much time thinking, explaining, and talking about a task, we start to feel that we&rsquo;ve gotten closer to achieving it. Or worse, when things get tough, we feel we can toss the whole project aside because we&rsquo;ve given it our best try, although of course we haven&rsquo;t.</p>

          <p>His primary means of effecting change was through the collection of pupils he mentored, protected, taught and inspired.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;To be somebody or to do something. In life there is often a roll call. That&rsquo;s when you will have to make a decision.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>&ldquo;To be or to do? Which way will you go?&rdquo;</p>

          <p>&ldquo;A man is worked upon by what he works on.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>The pretence of knowledge is our most dangerous vice, because it prevents us from getting any better. Studious self-assessment is the antidote.</p>

          <p>[...] the ego that puffs us up, the fear that makes us doubt ourselves, and any laziness that might make us want to coast.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;When student is ready, the teacher appears.</p>

          <p>The reality: We hear what we want to hear. We do what we feel like doing, and despite being incredibly busy and working very hard, we accomplish very little. Or worse, find ourselves in a mess we never anticipated.</p>

          <p>Purpose is about pursuing something outside yourself, as opposed to pleasuring yourself.</p>

          <p>It&rsquo;s a common attitude that transcends generations and societies. The angry, unappreciated genius is forced to do stuff she doesn&rsquo;t like, for people she doesn&rsquo;t respect, as she makes her way in the world.</p>

          <p>Greatness comes from humble beginnings; it comes from grunt work. It means you&rsquo;re the least important person in the room &mdash; until you change that with results.</p>

          <p>Find what nobody else wants to do and do it.</p>

          <p>[...] the person who clears the path ultimately controls its direction, just as the canvas shapes the painting.</p>

          <p>A person who thinks all the time has nothing to think about except thoughts, so he loses touch with reality and lives in a world of illusions.</p>

          <p>Out of the right speaker in you inner ear will come the endless stream of self-aggrandisement, the recitation of one&rsquo;s specialness, of how much more open and gifted and brilliant and knowing and misunderstood and humble one is. Out of the left speaker will be the rap songs of self-loathing, the lists of all the things one doesn&rsquo;t do well, of all the mistakes one has made today and over an entire lifetime, the doubt, the assertion that everything that one touches turns to shit, that one doesn&rsquo;t do relationships well, that one is in every way a fraud, incapable of selfless love, that one had no talent or insight and on and on and on.</p>

          <p>There&rsquo;s no one to perform for. There is just work to be done and lessons to be learned, in all that is around us.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;Vain men never hear anything but praise.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>What we don&rsquo;t protect ourselves against are people and things that make us feel good &mdash; or rather, too good.</p>

          <p>What am I avoiding, or running from, with my bluster, franticness, and embellishments?</p>

          <p>Not work until you get your big break, not work until you make a name for yourself, but work, work, work, forever and ever.</p>

          <p>Is it ten thousand hours or twenty thousand hours to mastery? The answer is that it doesn&rsquo;t matter. There is no end zone.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;Blessed are those servants whom the master finds awake when he comes.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>Make it so you don&rsquo;t have to fake it &mdash; that&rsquo;s the key.</p>

          <p>[...] your taste is good enough that you can tell what you&rsquo;re making is kind of a disappointment to you.</p>

          <p>Sobriety, open-mindedness, organization, and purpose &mdash; these are the great stabilizers. They balance out the ego and pride that come with achievement and recognition.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;It is hard to bear the results of good fortune suitably.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>We know that empires always fall, so we must think about why &mdash; and why they seem to always collapse from within.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;As our island of knowledge grows, so does the shore of our ignorance.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>No matter what you&rsquo;ve done up to this point, you better still be a student. If you&rsquo;re not still learning, you&rsquo;re already dying.</p>

          <p>Put yourself in rooms where you&rsquo;re the least knowledgeable person.</p>

          <p>[...] we&rsquo;re never happy with what we have, we want what others have too.</p>

          <p>All of us waste precious life doing things we don&rsquo;t like, to prove ourselves to people we don&rsquo;t respect, and to get things we don&rsquo;t want.</p>

          <p>So why do you do what you do? That&rsquo;s the question you need to answer. Stare at it until you can.</p>

          <p>In reality, we don&rsquo;t control the weather, we don&rsquo;t control the market, we don&rsquo;t control other people, and our efforts and energies in spite of this are pure waste.</p>

          <p>As you become successful in your own field, your responsibilities may begin to change. Days become less and less about doing and more and more about making decisions. Such is the nature of leadership.</p>

          <p>Creativity is a matter of receptiveness and recognition. This cannot happen if you&rsquo;re convinced the world revolves around you.</p>

          <p>We have to stand up for ourselves, right? But do we? So often, this is just ego, escalating tension more than dealing with it.</p>

          <p>Most successful people are people you&rsquo;ve never heard of. They want it that way. It keeps them sober. It helps them do their jobs.</p>

          <p>We don&rsquo;t need pity &mdash; our own or anyone else&rsquo;s &mdash; we need purpose, poise and patience.</p>

          <p>Almost without exception, this is what life does: it takes our plans and dashes them to pieces. Sometimes once, sometimes lots of times.</p>

          <p>Whether what you&rsquo;re going through is your fault or your problem doesn&rsquo;t matter, because it&rsquo;s yours to deal with right now.</p>

          <p>If ego holds sway, we&rsquo;ll accept nothing less than full appreciation.</p>

          <p>Maybe your parents will never be impressed. Maybe your girlfriend won&rsquo;t care. Maybe the investor won&rsquo;t see the numbers. Maybe the audience won&rsquo;t clap. But we have to be able to push through. We can&rsquo;t let that be what motivates us.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;Success is peace of mind, which is a direct result of self-satisfaction in knowing you made the effort to do your best to become the best that you are capable of becoming.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>&ldquo;The world breaks every one and afterward many are strong at the broken places. But those that will not break it kills.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>In 12-step groups, almost all the steps are about suppressing the ego and clearing out the entitlements and baggage and wreckage that has been accumulated &mdash; so that you might see what&rsquo;s left when all of that is stripped away and the real you is left.</p>

          <p>It can ruin your life only if it ruins your character.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;He who fears death will never do anything worthy of a living man.&rdquo;</p>

          <p>Your potential, the absolute best you&rsquo;re capable of &mdash; that&rsquo;s the metric to measure yourself against.</p>

          <p>&ldquo;See much, study much, suffer much, that is the path to wisdom.&rdquo;</p>
        </blockquote>
      </section>

